Setup & ConfigurationBefore starting, configure your identity so your commits are correctly attributed.git config --global user.name "[name]": Sets the name you want attached to your commit transactions.git config --global user.email "[email address]": Sets the email you want attached to your commit transactions.git version: Checks your currently installed Git version.Starting a ProjectInitialize a new project or copy an existing one from a remote server.git init: Initializes a brand new local repository in your current directory.git clone [url]: Downloads a project and its entire version history from a remote URL.The Basic Workflow (Staging & Committing)This is the daily cycle of saving your work locally.git status: Lists which files are modified, staged, or untracked.git add [file]: Adds a specific file to the staging area, preparing it for the next commit.git add .: Stages all modified and new files in the current directory.git commit -m "[message]": Records your staged changes as a permanent snapshot in history with a descriptive message.git commit --amend: Modifies the most recent commit (useful for fixing a typo in the message).Branching & MergingBranches allow you to work on features in isolation without breaking the main code.git branch: Lists all local branches in the current repository.git switch [branch-name]: Switches to the specified branch (modern replacement for git checkout).git switch -c [branch-name]: Creates a new branch and immediately switches to it.git merge [branch]: Combines the specified branch's history into your current branch.git branch -d [branch-name]: Deletes the specified local branch safely.Remote SynchronizationSync your local work with remote repositories like GitHub or GitLab.git remote add origin [url]: Connects your local repository to a remote server.git push origin [branch]: Uploads your local branch commits to the remote repository.git pull: Fetches changes from the remote and merges them into your current branch.git fetch: Downloads the latest history from the remote without merging it into your local files.Inspection & ComparisonsReview history and see what has changed over time.git log: Displays the full commit history for the current branch.git log --oneline: Shows a condensed version of the history (one line per commit).git diff: Shows the differences between files that are modified but not yet staged.git blame [file]: Shows who last changed each line of a file and when.Undoing ChangesUse these to fix mistakes or discard unwanted changes.git restore [file]: Discards unstaged changes in a file, reverting it to the last committed state.git reset --soft HEAD~1: Undoes the last commit but keeps your changes in the staging area.git reset --hard: Discards all local changes, both staged and unstaged, back to the last commit.git stash: Temporarily shelves (hides) modified tracked files to clean your working directory.git stash pop: Restores the most recently stashed changes and removes them from the stash list.